X:1
T:Loch Lomond
T:The Bonnie Banks o' Loch Lomond
C:Trad. Scottish (lyrics first published in Vocal Melodies of
C:Scotland, 1841; melody older, traditional)
S:Public domain (US) — both melody and 1841 lyrics are pre-1929.
N:Slow air for the 9-note Great Highland chanter, transposed and
N:adapted to A mixolydian. The original is a soprano-voice tune
N:in G major with a low D below the chanter range; the contour is
N:preserved here by raising those low notes into the chanter's
N:low octave.  NO RESTS — phrase ends are held tones, not silences.
M:4/4
L:1/8
Q:1/4=68
K:Amix
H:Range: low A (A4) to high A (A5). All nine chanter notes used.
H:Arrangement: Heifer Zephyr / Tony Koop, 2026 (MIT, sheet-music repo).
H:Slow-air phrasing: long held notes at phrase ends, with doublings
H:carrying the rhythmic weight that lyrics would otherwise carry.
H:Beginners can drop the doublings until the principal melody is
H:steady, then layer ornaments back in one phrase at a time.
% --- 16-bar slow air; AB form, each repeated ---
